Some More Details Denial of Service (DoS)
• Computers use an ICMP echo-reply message system, which is known as a
"ping," to test network connections. The system acts as a sonar between
devices. It sends a pulse, which emits an echo to provide an operator with
information about the network environment. When the connection works as
intended, source machines receive a reply from target machines.
• Ping commands are limited to a maximum size of 65,535 bytes.
• Attackers use ping commands to develop a Ping of Death command. They can
write a simple loop that allows them to execute the ping command with packet
sizes that exceed the 65,535-byte maximum level.
• Sending packets that are larger than 65,535 bytes violates the rules of IP.
• To avoid this, attackers will send packets in fragments that their target system
then attempts to piece together. When it does, the oversized packet will cause
a memory overflow.
Ping of Death (PoD)
Cyberattacks Common Types
