Some More Details
• The shrew attack specifically exploits a weakness in TCP’s retransmission
timeout (RTO) mechanism.
• Here’s how it works:
• The attacker employs man-in-the-middle techniques.
• They send short synchronized bursts of traffic to disrupt TCP connections on
the same link.
• When the client sends requests to the server the attacker sends a burst of
requests at the same time to a bottleneck router, causing the router to
suspend data transmission. Packets are dropped during RTO. After minRTO
the client retransmits the lost packets, considerably slowing TCP
transmission.
• By using this method the attacker uses minimal resources to reduce costs and
effort as well as making it harder to detect.
Shrew Attack
