Phishing
• A phishing attack is a fraudulent communication that appears to come from an
authentic source, often via email or text messages.
• The goal of phishing attack is to deceive users into revealing sensitive
information, such as login credentials, credit card numbers, or personal data.
• The impact of the phishing attack is not the attack itself, but how to use those
sensitive information to steal, modify, or even destroy certain assets.
Impact
Cyberattacks Common Types
Copyrights ©Dr. Ehab Abousaif - Topic: 2 Cyberattacks - 15
Phishing
• Impersonation: Scammers pretend to be a trusted entity, like a bank, utility
company, or online payment service. They might claim there’s a problem with
your account or a need to confirm personal or financial information.
• Urgency and Fear: Phishing messages often create a sense of urgency, urging
recipients to take immediate action. For instance, they might threaten account
suspension or claim unauthorized access.
• Suspicious Links and Attachments: Scammers include links or attachments that
lead to malicious websites or install malware. These links may appear
legitimate but can compromise your security.
• Spoofed Emails: Phishing emails may use logos and formatting similar to those
of legitimate companies. However, generic greetings, misspellings, or unusual
requests can give them away.
