Some More Details
• Cross-site scripting (XSS) is a client-side code injection attack. In an XSS attack,
the attacker attaches malicious code to a legitimate website. When a victim
loads that website, the injected code executes in their web browser.
• Client-side code runs on the user’s machine (in their browser). This code is
typically written in JavaScript. Examples of client-side code include JavaScript
used in interactive webpages and browser-based games.
• JavaScript in an XSS attack can access sensitive data, such as cookies. Attackers
can steal a user’s cookies and impersonate them online. It also can create HTTP
requests, allowing attackers to send stolen data (like cookies) back to
themselves.
