Some More Details
• DNS spoofing, also known as DNS cache poisoning, is a cyber attack that
corrupts DNS server entries. The attacker manipulates DNS records to redirect
users toward a malicious website instead of the correct IP address.
• How DNS Spoofing Works:
• DNS Server Compromise: The attacker directly hijacks a DNS server
configured to return a malicious IP address.
• Man-in-the-Middle (MITM): By exploiting weaknesses in an intermediate
name server’s caching system, the attacker intercepts communications
between users and a DNS server.
• Consequences of DNS Spoofing are:
• Data Theft: The attacker can steal sensitive data from users.
• Malware Installation: The malicious website can secretly install worms or
viruses on the user’s computer.
