• The attacker first intercepts the connection between the victim (the user being
attacked) and the target (the page under attack) using another type of man-inthe-middle attack.
• SSL hijacking is a type of attack where the attacker generates fake
certificates for the domains of HTTPS sites that the victim attempts to visit. As
a result, the victim assumes they have a secure connection to the target site,
but in reality, they have a secure connection to a cloned or proxy site
controlled by the attacker.
• The challenge with SSL hijacking lies in that browsers only trust certificates
signed by a trusted Certificate Authority (CA). To succeed, the attacker needs
to add their CA to the trusted certificate store in the victim’s operating system,
which often requires other attack vectors and vulnerabilities, such as phishing
or cross-site scripting.
